Women and children from Central America began arriving at the U.S.-Mexico border in unprecedented numbers during the summer of 2014.
The idea was to stop Central Americans from getting into Mexico, let alone the United States.
“They knew these networks existed and it would be really easy to find them and for somebody to come after them.” Advocacy groups say that U.S. support for Central American refugees has been inadequate.
